[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] An **adjective phrase** (or **adjectival phrase**) is a phrase whose head is an adjective.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Almost any grammar or syntax textbook or dictionary of linguistics terminology defines the adjective phrase in a similar way, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The **adjective** can initiate the phrase (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] *fond of steak*), conclude the phrase (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] *very happy*), or appear in a medial position (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The dependents of the head adjective—i.e. the other words and phrases inside the adjective phrase—are typically adverb or prepositional phrases, but they can also be clauses (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Adjectives and adjective phrases function in two basic ways, attributively or predicatively.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] An attributive adjective (phrase) precedes the noun of a noun phrase (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] A predicative adjective (phrase) follows a linking verb and serves to describe the preceding subject, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The adjective phrases are underlined in the following example sentences.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The distinguishing characteristic of an attributive adjective phrase is that it appears inside the noun phrase that it modifies.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] An interesting trait of these phrases in English is that an attributive adjective alone generally precedes the noun, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] *a proud man*, whereas a head-initial or head-medial adjective phrase follows its noun, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] A predicative adjective (phrase), in contrast, appears outside of the noun phrase that it describes, usually after a linking verb, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] There is a tendency to call a phrase an *adjectival phrase* when that phrase is functioning like an adjective phrase, but is not actually headed by an adjective.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] For example, in *Mr Clinton is a man of wealth*, the prepositional phrase *of wealth* modifies *a man* in a manner similar to how an adjective phrase would, and it can be reworded with an adjective, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] A more accurate term for such cases is *phrasal attributive* or *attributive phrase*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Constituency tests can also be used to identify adjectives and adjective phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Here are the three constituency tests, according to X-bar theory, that prove the adjective phrase is both a constituent, and an AP.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] **Ellipsis tests** can also be used to confirm if *very spicy* is an adjective phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] *Sam ordered a very spicy pizza, but the pizza Betty ordered was not very spicy.* This phrase passed the Ellipsis test, because no ambiguity is created and the adjective phrase could be elided (deleted).
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] A **movement test**, specifically pseudoclefting, can be used to confirm if *very spicy* is an adjective phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] *Sam ordered a very spicy pizza that was very spicy.* Movement tests not only prove that the constituent moved is a stand-alone constituent, but also proves that this phrase *very spicy* is an AP if drawn in a syntax tree.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Thus, because this adjective phrase could be moved to the right (pseudocleft), it's sufficient proof that it is both a constituent and an adjective phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Although constituency tests can prove the existence of an AP in a sentence, the meanings of these AP may be ambiguous.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] This ambiguity must be considered when considering the semantic versus pragmatic meaning.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Head adjectives that move to post-nominal position creates unambiguous interpretations.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The following examples show the different interpretive properties of pre- and post-nominal **adjectives** which are inside adjective phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] This example showed then entire adjective phrase moving, creating the same ambiguity as example 1.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Therefore, the placement of the adjective relative to the subject is important for creating unambiguous statements.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Unambiguous sentence: All the short people **blessed** were healed.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The adjective **blessed** is ambiguous in pre-nominal position because it creates a restrictive and a nonrestrictive interpretation (a), while in post-nominal position it only displays a restrictive interpretation (b).
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Plus, when the main adjective of the adjective phrase is moved to post-nominal position, only one interpretation is possible.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] There is cross-linguistic validity, according to the multiple articles referenced in Cinque's article, which studied this adjective placement in Italian as well.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Cinque discovered that exactly the same pattern was seen in Italian, because ambiguous interpretations only appeared when the adjective phrase was placed in pre-nominal position.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] Next, other research articles also confirm that this word order phenomenon exists in Mandarin Chinese, creating ambiguous interpretations.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] For example, an adjective phrase with the head adjective *private* in pre-object position, creates two interpretations.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] On the other hand, an adjective phrase with the head adjective *private* placed in post-object position only creates one interpretation.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The structure of adjective phrases (and of all other phrase types) can be represented using tree structures.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] There are two modern conventions for doing this, constituency-based trees of phrase structure grammars and dependency-based trees of dependency grammars.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The important aspect of these tree structures—regardless of whether one uses constituency or dependency to show the structure of phrases—is that they are identified as adjective phrases by the label on the top node of each tree.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The labels on the nodes in the trees are acronyms: A = adjective, Adv = adverb, AP = adjective phrase, N = noun/pronoun, P = preposition, PP = prepositional phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/adjective-phrase] The constituency trees identify these phrases as adjective phrases by labeling the top node with AP, and the dependency trees accomplish the same thing by positioning the A node at the top of the tree.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] In linguistics, an **adjunct** is an optional, or *structurally dispensable*, part of a sentence, clause, or phrase that, if removed or discarded, will not structurally affect the remainder of the sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Example: In the sentence *John helped Bill in Central Park*, the phrase *in Central Park* is an adjunct.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] A more detailed definition of the adjunct emphasizes its attribute as a modifying form, word, or phrase that depends on another form, word, or phrase, being an element of clause structure with adverbial function.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] An adjunct is not an argument (nor is it a predicative expression), and an argument is not an adjunct.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The argument–adjunct distinction is central in most theories of syntax and semantics.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The terminology used to denote arguments and adjuncts can vary depending on the theory at hand.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Some dependency grammars, for instance, employ the term *circonstant* (instead of *adjunct*), following Tesnière (1959).
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The area of grammar that explores the nature of predicates, their arguments, and adjuncts is called valency theory.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Predicates have valency; they determine the number and type of arguments that can or must appear in their environment.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The valency of predicates is also investigated in terms of subcategorization.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] An *adverbial adjunct* is a sentence element that often establishes the circumstances in which the action or state expressed by the verb takes place.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Notice that this example is ambiguous between whether the adjunct *in the garden* modifies the verb *saw* (in which case it is Lorna who saw the dog while she was in the garden) or the noun phrase *the dog* (in which case it is the dog who is in the garden).
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The definition can be extended to include adjuncts that modify nouns or other parts of speech (see noun adjunct).
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] An adjunct can be a single word, a phrase, or an entire clause.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Most discussions of adjuncts focus on adverbial adjuncts, that is, on adjuncts that modify verbs, verb phrases, or entire clauses like the adjuncts in the three examples just given.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts can appear in other domains, however; that is, they can modify most categories.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] An **adnominal** adjunct is one that modifies a noun: for a list of possible types of these, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts that modify adjectives and adverbs are occasionally called *adadjectival* and *adadverbial*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Each of the adjuncts in the examples throughout this article is a constituent.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts can be categorized in terms of the functional meaning that they contribute to the phrase, clause, or sentence in which they appear.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Causal adjuncts establish the reason for, or purpose of, an action or state.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Concessive adjuncts establish contrary circumstances.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Conditional adjuncts establish the condition in which an action occurs or state holds.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Consecutive adjuncts establish an effect or result.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Final adjuncts establish the goal of an action (what one wants to accomplish).
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Instrumental adjuncts establish the instrument used to accomplish an action.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Locative adjuncts establish where, to where, or from where a state or action happened or existed.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Modal adjuncts establish the extent to which the speaker views the action or state as (im)probable.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Modificative adjuncts establish how the action happened or the state existed.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] – Temporal adjuncts establish when, how long, or how frequent the action or state happened or existed.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts and predicates is central to most theories of syntax and grammar.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Predicates take arguments and they permit (certain) adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The arguments of a predicate are necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The adjuncts of a predicate, in contrast, provide auxiliary information about the core predicate-argument meaning, which means they are not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts and arguments can be identified using various diagnostics.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The omission diagnostic, for instance, helps identify many arguments and thus many possible adjuncts as well.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] If a given constituent cannot be omitted from a sentence, clause, or phrase without resulting in an unacceptable expression, that constituent is *not* an adjunct.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] In contrast, if a given constituent can be omitted without affecting grammaticality or core meaning, that constituent *is* an adjunct.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] I know. - the sentence is acceptable, but its meaning is changed entirely.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Further diagnostics used to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts include multiplicity, distance from head, and the ability to coordinate.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] is a noun phrase that functions as object argument.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is much less clear than the simple omission diagnostic (and the other diagnostics) suggests.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Most accounts of the argument vs. adjunct distinction acknowledge a further division.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] One distinguishes between obligatory and optional arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Optional arguments pattern like adjuncts when just the omission diagnostic is employed, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] is not an obligatory argument, but it could be (and it is) an optional argument.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The existence of optional arguments blurs the line between arguments and adjuncts considerably.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Further diagnostics (beyond the omission diagnostic and the others mentioned above) must be employed to distinguish between adjuncts and optional arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] One such diagnostic is the relative clause test.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The test constituent is moved from the matrix clause to a subordinate relative clause containing *which occurred/happened*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] is not an adjunct, which means it must be an optional argument.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The particular merit of the relative clause test is its ability to distinguish between many argument and adjunct PPs, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The reliability of the relative clause diagnostic is actually limited.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] For instance, it incorrectly suggests that many modal and manner adjuncts are arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] This fact bears witness to the difficulty of providing an absolute diagnostic for the distinctions currently being examined.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Despite the difficulties, most theories of syntax and grammar distinguish on the one hand between arguments and adjuncts and on the other hand between optional arguments and adjuncts, and they grant a central position to these divisions in the overarching theory.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Many phrases have the outward appearance of an adjunct but are in fact (part of) a predicate instead.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The confusion occurs often with copular verbs, in particular with a form of *be*, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The PPs in these sentences are neither adjuncts nor arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The preposition in each case is, rather, part of the main predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The matrix predicate in the first sentence is *is under*; this predicate takes the two arguments *It* and *the bush*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Similarly, the matrix predicate in the second sentence is *is at*; this predicate takes the two arguments *The party* and *seven o'clock*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Distinguishing between predicates, arguments, and adjuncts becomes particularly difficult when secondary predicates are involved, for instance with resultative predicates, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The resultative adjective *tired* can be viewed as an argument of the matrix predicate *made*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] But it is also definitely a predicate over *him*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Such examples illustrate that distinguishing predicates, arguments, and adjuncts can become difficult and there are many cases where a given expression functions in more ways than one.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] This overview acknowledges three types of entities: predicates, arguments, and adjuncts, whereby arguments are further divided into obligatory and optional ones.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Many theories of syntax and grammar employ trees to represent the structure of sentences.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Various conventions are used to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts in these trees.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] In phrase structure grammars, many adjuncts are distinguished from arguments insofar as the adjuncts of a head predicate will appear higher in the structure than the object argument(s) of that predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The adjunct is adjoined to a projection of the head predicate above and to the right of the object argument, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The object argument each time is identified insofar as it is a sister of V that appears to the right of V, and the adjunct status of the adverb *early* and the PP *before class* is seen in the higher position to the right of and above the object argument.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Other adjuncts, in contrast, are assumed to adjoin to a position that is between the subject argument and the head predicate or above and to the left of the subject argument, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The subject is identified as an argument insofar as it appears as a sister and to the left of V(P).
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The modal adverb *certainly* is shown as an adjunct insofar as it adjoins to an intermediate projection of V or to a projection of S.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] In X-bar theory, adjuncts are represented as elements that are sisters to X' levels and daughters of X' level [X' adjunct [X'...]].
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Theories that assume sentence structure to be less layered than the analyses just given sometimes employ a special convention to distinguish adjuncts from arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] Some dependency grammars, for instance, use an arrow dependency edge to mark adjuncts, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The arrow dependency edge points away from the adjunct toward the governor of the adjunct.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The arrows identify six adjuncts: *Yesterday*, *probably*, *many times*, *very*, *very long*, and *that you like*.
[src:noun-phrase/adjunct-grammar] The standard, non-arrow dependency edges identify *Sam*, *Susan*, *that very long story that you like*, etc. as arguments (of one of the predicates in the sentence).
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] An **adverb** is a word or an expression that generally modifies a verb, an adjective, another adverb, a determiner, a clause, a preposition, or a sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, or level of certainty by answering questions such as *how*, *in what way*, *when*, *where*, *to what extent*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] This is called the adverbial function and may be performed by an individual adverb, by an adverbial phrase, or by an adverbial clause.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] The English word *adverb* derives (through French) from Latin *adverbium*, from *ad-* ('to'), *verbum* ('word', 'verb'), and the nominal suffix *- ium*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] The term implies that the principal function of adverbs is to act as modifiers of verbs or verb phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] An adverb used in this way may provide information about the manner, place, time, frequency, certainty, or other circumstances of the activity denoted by the verb or verb phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Adverbs can also be used as modifiers of adjectives, and of other adverbs, often to indicate degree.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Adverbs thus perform a wide range of modifying functions.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] The major exception is the function of modifier of nouns, which is performed instead by adjectives (compare *she sang loudly* with *her loud singing disturbed me*; here the verb *sang* is modified by the adverb *loudly*, whereas the noun *singing* is modified by the adjective *loud*).
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] The word *even* in the first sentence is an adjective, since it is a prepositive modifier that modifies the noun *numbers*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] When the function of an adverb is performed by an expression consisting of more than one word, it is called an adverbial phrase or adverbial clause, or simply an adverbial.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] In English, adverbs of manner (answering the question *how?*) are often formed by adding *-ly* to adjectives, but flat adverbs (such as in *drive fast*, *drive slow*, and *drive friendly*) have the same form as the corresponding adjective.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Many other adverbs, however, are not related to adjectives in this way; they may be derived from other words or phrases, or may be single morphemes.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Examples of such adverbs in English include *here, there, together, yesterday, aboard, very, almost*, etc.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Where the meaning permits, adverbs may undergo comparison, taking comparative and superlative forms.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] In English this is usually done by adding *more* and *most* before the adverb (*more slowly, most slowly*), although there are a few adverbs that take inflected forms, such as *well*, for which *better* and *best* are used.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] For more information about the formation and use of adverbs in English, see English adverbs.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] For other languages, see § In other languages below, and the articles on individual languages and their grammars.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Adverbs are considered a part of speech in traditional English grammar, and are still included as a part of speech in grammar taught in schools and used in dictionaries.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] However, modern grammarians recognize that words traditionally grouped together as adverbs serve a number of different functions.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Some describe adverbs as a "catch-all" category that includes all words that do not belong to one of the other parts of speech.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] A logical approach to dividing words into classes relies on recognizing which words can be used in a certain context.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] When this approach is taken, it is seen that adverbs fall into a number of different categories.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] For example, some adverbs can be used to modify an entire sentence, whereas others cannot.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Even when a sentential adverb has other functions, the meaning is often not the same.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Words like *very* afford another example.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] *Perry is very fast* is grammatical, but not *Perry very won the race*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] These words can modify adjectives but not verbs.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] On the other hand, there are words like *here* and *there* that cannot modify adjectives.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] *The sock looks good there* is grammatical, but not *It is a there beautiful sock*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] The fact that many adverbs can be used in more than one of these functions can confuse the issue, and it may seem like splitting hairs to say that a single adverb is really two or more words that serve different functions.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] However, this distinction can be useful, especially when considering adverbs like *naturally* that have different meanings in their different functions.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Rodney Huddleston distinguishes between a *word* and a *lexicogrammatical-word*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Grammarians find difficulty categorizing negating words, such as the English *not*.
[src:noun-phrase/adverb] Although traditionally listed as an adverb, this word does not behave grammatically like any other, and it probably should be placed in a class of its own.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] In English grammar, an **adverbial** (abbreviated **adv**) is a word (an adverb) or a group of words (an adverbial clause or adverbial phrase) that modifies or more closely defines the sentence or the verb.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Adverbials most commonly take the form of adverbs, adverb phrases, temporal noun phrases or prepositional phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Many types of adverbials (for instance: reason and condition) are often expressed by clauses.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] An adverbial is a construction which modifies or describes verbs.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] When an adverbial modifies a verb, it changes the meaning of that verb.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] This may be performed by an adverb or a word group, either considered an adverbial: for example, a prepositional phrase, a noun phrase, a finite clause or a non-finite clause.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Adverbial complements (i.e. obligatory adverbial) are adverbials that render a sentence ungrammatical and meaningless if removed.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Adjuncts: These are part of the core meaning of the sentence, but if omitted still leave a meaningful sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Conjuncts: These link two sentences together.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Disjuncts: These make comments on the meaning of the rest of the sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] All verb- or sentence-modifying adjuncts are adverbials, but some adverbials are not adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Prepositions (*in*, *out*, etc.) may be used adverbially to indicate direction or location.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] In some grammar models, negators such as "not" and "never" are considered adverbs with the function of negating adverbial clauses.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Often ignored, expletives may take up many adverbial syntactic functions.
[src:noun-phrase/adverbial] Pragmatically and semantically, they often serve as intensifiers, boosting the content of the clause they appear in.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He collated the text of Theophilus' Greek paraphrasis of Justinian's *Institutes* but failed to finish his extensive work in this field.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] However, his translation of Theophilus was published in 2010 as the parallel English text accompanying the Greek in the new edition.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He also wrote two biographical works in Scottish history: *Sir William Wallace* (1898) and *King Robert the Bruce* (1899) in the *Famous Scots Series* published by Oliphant, Anderson and Ferrier.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] Lack of money took him into journalism and he was editor of the *Educational Times* (now the Times Educational Supplement) from 1902 to 1912 and on the staff of the Daily Chronicle.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He died on 8 June 1934 at his home in Clapham Common, London.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] Murison was born at New Deer, Aberdeenshire, Scotland on 3 March 1847.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He was born to a crofting family and looked after cattle as a boy.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He won a bursary to Aberdeen Grammar School where he excelled and won a scholarship to the University of Aberdeen.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] After achieving a first class honours M.A. degree in classics, he returned to his old school and was an English Master there from 1869 to 1876.
[src:noun-phrase/alexander-murison] He married Elizabeth Logan in 1870 and they had two children, Alexander Logan (1871–1948) and Sir James William Murison (1872–1945), who became Chief Justice of the Straits Settlements.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] Radford began researching the syntax of colloquial English in 2010, using data recorded from unscripted radio and TV broadcasts.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] On this topic, he produced a research monograph and various articles, and pursued further research on syntax of relative clauses in colloquial English.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] From January 2014 until the time of his death, Radford was an Emeritus Professor of the Department of Language and Linguistics at the University of Essex.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] Radford pursued undergraduate studies at Trinity College, Cambridge, reading Modern Languages (French, Italian and Romanian), Linguistics and Romance Philology.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] He graduated with a first-class degree and was awarded a research scholarship by Trinity College, Cambridge.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] He completed a PhD on Italian syntax there, supervised by Pieter Seuren.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] In 1980, he became Professor of Linguistics at the University College of North Wales, serving first as Head of the Department of Linguistics (1980–87), and later as Head of the School of Modern Languages and Linguistics (1987–89).
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] In 1989, he returned to the University of Essex as Professor of Linguistics, where he served three terms as Head of the Department of Language and Linguistics, and one as Dean of the School of Humanities and Comparative Studies.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] He retired at the end of 2013, and acquired the status of Emeritus Professor.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] He served on the editorial board of the *Journal of Linguistics*, *Journal of Child Language*, *Studies in Theoretical Psycholinguistics*, *Studies in Language Sciences*, *Chomskyan Studies*, *Rivista di Grammatica Generativa*, and *Iberia*.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] He also served two spells as a member of the Linguistics Review Panel for the Higher Education Funding Council for England.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] In his 1990 book, *Syntactic Theory and the Acquisition of English Syntax*, Radford summarizes the state of a maturation hypothesis for child language acquisition.
[src:noun-phrase/andrew-radford-linguist] This led to an analysis that described children as gradually building up increasingly complex structure, with *Lexical/thematic stage-1* (lexical categories like noun and verb) preceding *Functional/syntactic stage-2* (functional categories like determiner and complementiser).
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In linguistics, an **argument** is an expression that helps complete the meaning of a predicate, the latter referring in this context to a main verb and its auxiliaries.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In this regard, the *complement* is a closely related concept.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Most predicates take one, two, or three arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] A predicate and its arguments form a *predicate–argument structure*.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The discussion of predicates and arguments is associated most with (content) verbs and noun phrases (NPs), although other syntactic categories can also be construed as predicates and as arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Arguments must be distinguished from adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] While a predicate needs its arguments to complete its meaning, the adjuncts that appear with a predicate are optional; they are not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Most theories of syntax and semantics acknowledge arguments and adjuncts, although the terminology varies, and the distinction is generally believed to exist in all languages.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Dependency grammars sometimes call arguments *actants*, following Lucien Tesnière (1959).
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Predicates have a valence; they determine the number and type of arguments that can or must appear in their environment.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The valence of predicates is also investigated in terms of subcategorization.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The basic analysis of the syntax and semantics of clauses relies heavily on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The clause predicate, which is often a content verb, demands certain arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] That is, the arguments are necessary in order to complete the meaning of the verb.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The adjuncts that appear, in contrast, are not necessary in this sense.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The subject phrase and object phrase are the two most frequently occurring arguments of verbal predicates.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Each of these sentences contains two arguments (in bold), the first noun (phrase) being the subject argument, and the second the object argument.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] *Jill*, for example, is the subject argument of the predicate *likes*, and *Jack* is its object argument.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Verbal predicates that demand just a subject argument (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] *sleep*, *work*, *relax*) are intransitive, verbal predicates that demand an object argument as well (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] *like*, *fry*, *help*) are transitive, and verbal predicates that demand two object arguments are ditransitive (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] When additional information is added to our three example sentences, one is dealing with adjuncts, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The added phrases (in bold) are adjuncts; they provide additional information that is not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate *likes*.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] One key difference between arguments and adjuncts is that the appearance of a given argument is often obligatory, whereas adjuncts appear optionally.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] While typical verb arguments are subject or object nouns or noun phrases as in the examples above, they can also be prepositional phrases (PPs) (or even other categories).
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Subject and object arguments are known as *core arguments*; core arguments can be suppressed, added, or exchanged in different ways, using voice operations like passivization, antipassivization, applicativization, incorporation, etc.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Prepositional arguments, which are also called *oblique arguments*, however, do not tend to undergo the same processes.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic theories must explain how syntactic representations are built incrementally during sentence comprehension.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Argument status determines the cognitive mechanism in which a phrase will be attached to the developing syntactic representations of a sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic evidence supports a formal distinction between arguments and adjuncts, for any questions about the argument status of a phrase are, in effect, questions about learned mental representations of the lexical heads.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] An important distinction acknowledges both syntactic and semantic arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Content verbs determine the number and type of syntactic arguments that can or must appear in their environment; they impose specific syntactic functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, specific preposition, possessor, etc.) onto their arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] These syntactic functions will vary as the form of the predicate varies (e.g. active verb, passive participle, gerund, nominal, etc.).
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In languages that have morphological case, the arguments of a predicate must appear with the correct case markings (e.g. nominative, accusative, dative, genitive, etc.) imposed on them by their predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The semantic arguments of the predicate, in contrast, remain consistent, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The predicate 'like' appears in various forms in these examples, which means that the syntactic functions of the arguments associated with *Jack* and *Jill* vary.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The object of the active sentence, for instance, becomes the subject of the passive sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Despite this variation in syntactic functions, the arguments remain semantically consistent.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In each case, *Jill* is the experiencer (= the one doing the liking) and *Jack* is the one being experienced (= the one being liked).
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In other words, the syntactic arguments are subject to syntactic variation in terms of syntactic functions, whereas the thematic roles of the arguments of the given predicate remain consistent as the form of that predicate changes.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The syntactic arguments of a given verb can also vary across languages.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] For example, the verb *put* in English requires three syntactic arguments: subject, object, locative (e. g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] These syntactic arguments correspond to the three semantic arguments agent, theme, and goal.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The Japanese verb *oku* 'put', in contrast, has the same three semantic arguments, but the syntactic arguments differ, since Japanese does not require three syntactic arguments, so it is correct to say *Kare ga hon o oita* ("He put the book").
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The equivalent sentence in English is ungrammatical without the required locative argument, as the examples involving *put* above demonstrate.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] For this reason, a slight paraphrase is required to render the nearest grammatical equivalent in English: *He positioned the book* or *He deposited the book*.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] A large body of literature has been devoted to distinguishing arguments from adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Numerous syntactic tests have been devised for this purpose.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] One such test is the relative clause diagnostic.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] If the test constituent can appear after the combination *which occurred/happened* in a relative clause, it is an adjunct, not an argument, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The same diagnostic results in unacceptable relative clauses (and sentences) when the test constituent is an argument, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The utility of the relative clause test is, however, limited.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] It incorrectly suggests, for instance, that modal adverbs (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] *probably*, *certainly*, *maybe*) and manner expressions (e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] *quickly*, *carefully*, *totally*) are arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] If a constituent passes the relative clause test, however, one can be sure that it is *not* an argument.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] A further division blurs the line between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Many arguments behave like adjuncts with respect to another diagnostic, the omission diagnostic.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Adjuncts can always be omitted from the phrase, clause, or sentence in which they appear without rendering the resulting expression unacceptable.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Some arguments (obligatory ones), in contrast, cannot be omitted.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] There are many other arguments, however, that are identified as arguments by the relative clause diagnostic but that can nevertheless be omitted, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The relative clause diagnostic would identify the constituents in bold as arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The omission diagnostic here, however, demonstrates that they are not obligatory arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The insight, then, is that a three-way division is needed.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] On the one hand, one distinguishes between arguments and adjuncts, and on the other hand, one allows for a further division between obligatory and optional arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Most work on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts has been conducted at the clause level and has focused on arguments and adjuncts to verbal predicates.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The distinction is crucial for the analysis of noun phrases as well, however.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] If it is altered somewhat, the relative clause diagnostic can also be used to distinguish arguments from adjuncts in noun phrases, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The diagnostic identifies *Bill's* and *of the poem* as arguments, and *bold* and *after lunch* as adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is often indicated in the tree structures used to represent syntactic structure.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In phrase structure grammars, an adjunct is "adjoined" to a projection of its head predicate in such a manner that distinguishes it from the arguments of that predicate.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The distinction is quite visible in theories that employ the X-bar schema, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The complement argument appears as a sister of the head X, and the specifier argument appears as a daughter of XP.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The optional adjuncts appear in one of a number of positions adjoined to a bar-projection of X or to XP.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Theories of syntax that acknowledge n-ary branching structures and hence construe syntactic structure as being flatter than the layered structures associated with the X-bar schema must employ some other means to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In this regard, some dependency grammars employ an arrow convention.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Arguments receive a "normal" dependency edge, whereas adjuncts receive an arrow edge.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The arrow edges in the tree identify four constituents (= complete subtrees) as adjuncts: *At one time*, *actually*, *in congress*, and *for fun*.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The normal dependency edges (= non-arrows) identify the other constituents as arguments of their heads.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Thus *Sam*, *a duck*, and *to his representative in congress* are identified as arguments of the verbal predicate *wanted to send*.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Argumentation theory focuses on how logical reasoning leads to end results through an internal structure built of premises, a method of reasoning and a conclusion.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] There are many versions of argumentation that relate to this theory that include: conversational, mathematical, scientific, interpretive, legal, and political.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Grammar theory, specifically functional theories of grammar, relate to the functions of language as the link to fully understanding linguistics by referencing grammar elements to their functions and purposes.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] A variety of theories exist regarding the structure of syntax, including generative grammar, categorial grammar, and dependency grammar.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Modern theories of semantics include formal semantics, lexical semantics, and computational semantics.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Formal semantics focuses on truth conditioning.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Lexical Semantics delves into word meanings in relation to their context and computational semantics uses algorithms and architectures to investigate linguistic meanings.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The concept of valence is the number and type of arguments that are linked to a predicate, in particular to a verb.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] In valence theory verbs' arguments include also the argument expressed by the subject of the verb.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The notion of argument structure was first conceived in the 1980s by researchers working in the government–binding framework to help address controversies about arguments.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is crucial to most theories of syntax and grammar.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Arguments behave differently from adjuncts in numerous ways.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] Theories of binding, coordination, discontinuities, ellipsis, etc. must acknowledge and build on the distinction.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] When one examines these areas of syntax, what one finds is that arguments consistently behave differently from adjuncts and that without the distinction, our ability to investigate and understand these phenomena would be seriously hindered.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] There is a distinction between arguments and adjuncts which is not really noticed by many in everyday language.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] The difference is between obligatory phrases versus phrases which embellish a sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] For instance, if someone says "Tim punched the stuffed animal", the phrase stuffed animal would be an argument because it is the main part of the sentence.
[src:noun-phrase/argument-linguistics] If someone says, "Tim punched the stuffed animal with glee", the phrase with glee would be an adjunct because it just enhances the sentence and the sentence can stand alone without it.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] A **noun phrase** – or **NP** or **nominal (phrase)** – is a phrase that usually has a noun or pronoun as its head, and has the same grammatical functions as a noun.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Noun phrases are very common cross-linguistically, and they may be the most frequently occurring phrase type.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Noun phrases often function as verb subjects and objects, as predicative expressions, and as complements of prepositions.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] One NP can be embedded inside another NP; for instance, *some of his constituents* has as a constituent the shorter NP *his constituents*.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In some theories of grammar, noun phrases with determiners are analyzed as having the determiner as the head of the phrase, see for instance Chomsky (1995) and Hudson (1990).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Some examples of noun phrases are underlined in the sentences below.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can be identified by the possibility of pronoun substitution, as is illustrated in the examples below.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] A string of words that can be replaced by a single pronoun without rendering the sentence grammatically unacceptable is a noun phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] As to whether the string must contain at least two words, see the following section.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Traditionally, a phrase is understood to contain two or more words.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The traditional progression in the size of syntactic units is *word < phrase < clause*, and in this approach a single word (such as a noun or pronoun) would not be referred to as a phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] However, many modern schools of syntax – especially those that have been influenced by X-bar theory – make no such restriction.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Here many single words are judged to be phrases based on a desire for theory-internal consistency.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] A phrase is deemed to be a word or a combination of words that appears in a set syntactic position, for instance in subject position or object position.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The words in bold are called phrases since they appear in the syntactic positions where multiple-word phrases (i.e. traditional phrases) can appear.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] This practice takes the constellation to be primitive rather than the words themselves.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The word *he*, for instance, functions as a pronoun, but within the sentence it also functions as a noun phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The phrase structure grammars of the Chomskyan tradition (government and binding theory and the minimalist program) are primary examples of theories that apply this understanding of phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Other grammars such as dependency grammars are likely to reject this approach to phrases, since they take the words themselves to be primitive.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For them, phrases must contain two or more words.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] A typical noun phrase consists of a noun (the head of the phrase) together with zero or more dependents of various types.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The allowability, form and position of these elements depend on the syntax of the language in question.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In English, determiners, adjectives (and some adjective phrases) and noun modifiers precede the head noun, whereas the heavier units – phrases and clauses – generally follow it.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] This is part of a strong tendency in English to place heavier constituents to the right, making English more of a head-initial language.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Japanese and Turkish) are more likely to place all modifiers before the head noun.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Other languages, such as French, often place even single-word adjectives after the noun.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Noun phrases can take different forms than that described above, for example when the head is a pronoun rather than a noun, or when elements are linked with a coordinating conjunction such as *and*, *or*, *but*.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For more information about the structure of noun phrases in English, see English grammar § Phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Noun phrases typically bear argument functions.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] That is, the syntactic functions that they fulfill are those of the arguments of the main clause predicate, particularly those of subject, object and predicative expression.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] They also function as arguments in such constructs as participial phrases and prepositional phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Sometimes a noun phrase can also function as an adjunct of the main clause predicate, thus taking on an adverbial function, e.g.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The situation is complicated by the fact that in some contexts a noun phrase may nonetheless be used without a determiner (as in *I like big houses*); in this case the phrase may be described as having a "null determiner".
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In the original X-bar theory, the two respective types of entity are called noun phrase (NP) and N-bar (N, N′).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Thus in the sentence *Here is the big house*, both *house* and *big house* are N-bars, while *the big house* is a noun phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In the sentence *I like big houses*, both *houses* and *big houses* are N-bars, but *big houses* also functions as a noun phrase (in this case without an explicit determiner).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In some modern theories of syntax, however, what are called "noun phrases" above are no longer considered to be headed by a noun, but by the determiner (which may be null), and they are thus called *determiner phrases* (DP) instead of noun phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] This analysis of noun phrases is widely referred to as the *DP hypothesis*.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] It has been the preferred analysis of noun phrases in the minimalist program from its start (since the early 1990s), though the arguments in its favor tend to be theory-internal.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] By taking the determiner, a function word, to be head over the noun, a structure is established that is analogous to the structure of the finite clause, with a complementizer.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Apart from the minimalist program, however, the DP hypothesis is rejected by most other modern theories of syntax and grammar, in part because these theories lack the relevant functional categories.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, for instance, almost all assume the traditional NP analysis of noun phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For illustrations of different analyses of noun phrases depending on whether the DP hypothesis is rejected or accepted, see the next section.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The representation of noun phrases using parse trees depends on the basic approach to syntactic structure adopted.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The layered trees of many phrase structure grammars grant noun phrases an intricate structure that acknowledges a hierarchy of functional projections.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Dependency grammars, in contrast, since the basic architecture of dependency places a major limitation on the amount of structure that the theory can assume, produce simple, relatively flat structures for noun phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The representation also depends on whether the noun or the determiner is taken to be the head of the phrase (see the discussion of the DP hypothesis in the previous section).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] Below are some possible trees for the two noun phrases *the big house* and *big houses* (as in the sentences *Here is the big house* and *I like big houses*).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The following trees represent a more complex phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For simplicity, only dependency-based trees are given.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The first tree is based on the traditional assumption that nouns, rather than determiners, are the heads of phrases.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The head noun *picture* has the four dependents *the*, *old*, *of Fred*, and *that I found in the drawer*.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The tree shows how the lighter dependents appear as pre-dependents (preceding their head) and the heavier ones as post-dependents (following their head).
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The second tree assumes the DP hypothesis, namely that determiners serve as phrase heads, rather than nouns.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] The determiner *the* is now depicted as the head of the entire phrase, thus making the phrase a determiner phrase.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] There is still a noun phrase present (*old picture of Fred that I found in the drawer*) but this phrase is below the determiner.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] An early conception of the noun phrase can be found in *First work in English* by Alexander Murison.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] In this conception a noun phrase is "the infinitive of the verb" (p.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] 146), which may appear "in any position in the sentence where a noun may appear".
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For example, *to be just is more important than to be generous* has two underlined infinitives which may be replaced by nouns, as in *justice is more important than generosity*.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] This same conception can be found in subsequent grammars, such as 1878's *A Tamil Grammar* or 1882's *Murby's English grammar and analysis*, where the conception of an X phrase is a phrase that can stand in for X.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] By 1912, the concept of a noun phrase as being based around a noun can be found, for example, "an adverbial noun phrases is a group of words of which the noun is the base word, that tells the time or place of an action, or how long, how far, or how much".
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] By 1924, the idea of a noun phrase being a noun plus dependents seems to be established.
[src:noun-phrase/noun-phrase] For example, "Note order of words in noun-phrase--noun + adj. + genitive" suggests a more modern conception of noun phrases.
